snippet.textDisplay: Actually, I think the problem was not the software. The CPU uses cache in order not to wait for RAM for every code that we want to execute. And since you opened that much of tabs, the cache miss rate increased abnormally. Thus, basically, the CPU has to wait the RAM for each instruction it wants to execute which slows down the processor a lot. I mean A LOT. A typical RAM is approx. 200 times slower, but in this case as you said the RAM's are not directly connected, so they are much more slower than a normal RAM. Probably 3-4 orders of magnitude slower than cache. That's the reason why you have to wait for 30 sec just for a right click.

snippet.textDisplay:
2 things: First, you really should disable virtual memory / paging when doing a test like this. You didn't mention anything about it one way or the other, so I'm assuming you didn't disable it.

Secondly, I'm currently using a laptop with 16 GB of RAM and I'm running Chrome with about 70 tabs open (plus another 40 or so subframes, which could arguably count as separate tabs as well) and I'm sitting at 3.6 GB of RAM used by Chrome. I also have a bunch of other stuff running, like 2 instances of Visual Studio, Teams, Outlook, SSMS, Edge (about 15 tabs in there), Process Explorer, and various other things running in the background like webroot, OpenVPN, etc. In total, my system is using 14 GB of RAM. And this is very normal for me. So I can tell you with certainty that Chrome does manage it's memory very well and it can discard or freeze tabs that haven't been used recently, freeing up that memory for other tabs. Check out chrome://discards/ to see the status of all your tabs and if they are discarded and how recently they've been used. You really should have had this open the for the whole test, as well as the Chrome Task Manager perhaps.

So I don't think that opening a ton of tabs in Chrome is really going to give you a good test of how much stuff you can shove into RAM. Especially not when you're just opening the exact same pages over and over again. The growth curve is nowhere close to being linear. For example, you said that opening all 20 tabs in a new window caused the memory to jump from 5 GB (0.25/tab) to 5.8 GB (0.145/tab). Then at 200 tabs, it was 10 GB (0.05/tab). 600 tabs was 19.5 GB (0.0325/tab), 900 tabs was 28.5 GB (0.03167/tab), and then the tab counts and memory updates got a bit chopped up and I couldn't tell exactly what they were any more, but the final count was 6,000 tabs at about 187 GB total RAM used, so not just Chrome usage anymore and I'll just have to assume it was probably around 180 GB used by Chrome. You mentioned that it jumped to 200 GB total RAM used, but that was also after you said that Gimp was loading up OK, so I don't know if that was from Gimp taking up a bunch of extra memory or if it was from you interacting with a bunch of the Chrome windows that might have been discarded or frozen.


Notice also that the number of Chrome processes stayed in the range of about 90 - 105 the whole time (or at least for the whole time that it was visible in the video). I'm thinking though that Chrome probably has a limited number of processes/threads that it can use for UI functions, which is why it became unusable while the rest of the computer seemed to be able to run without much difficulty. I think that a much better test would be to load up a bunch of different programs at once, one of them being Chrome with somewhere around 200 tabs open, each of them being a completely different page (not necessarily a different site though, like you could load up several different YouTube videos, just not the YouTube homepage over and over again). Have some of them be memory intensive programs, like AutoCAD or some other 3D software with a really complex scene loaded in with tons of highly detailed objects.

The thing is that programmers, when working on software that is memory intensive, will try to use every trick possible to manage the memory efficiently so that there's not a bunch of data sitting in memory that we don't need right away. This tends to be a trade off where more CPU and I/O is used in order to reduce the memory requirements, but since those are time based resources while the RAM is actually a fixed resource, this is usually a worthwhile trade off. It'll mean that it will be using more of the CPU and will be reading stuff from the disk or network more often, but those things only slow down the process a little, they don't prevent the process from completing at all like you would see if you couldn't load your data into memory. This means that with a system that is so absurdly overbalanced as to have 2 TB of RAM on a single CPU server board, you will have a very hard time getting the memory to fill up without loading up a bunch of different programs, and will likely kill your CPU before you get to 50% on the RAM.

snippet.textDisplay:
looks like an issue with both chrome and windows. every chromium process is aware of the others to allow you to merge windows, and would therefore access shared memory by the entire of chrome, this could potentially cause a slowdown. the next potential issue is that with 6000 chrome tabs, thats 6000 chrome processes, it may not look like a lot of cpu resources are being used but they are, just not in the way you expect. in this case, windows is scheduling (and each chromium process in the user space) the execution of the threads, therefore, with 6000 processes, each with multiple threads, to keep them all running, each core alone has to handle literally hundreds of just chromium threads in realtime, and is most likely switching between threads too often to avoid starving other threads. this gives no single thread enough time to execute anything useful quickly, resulting in massive slowdowns. basically, cpu utilisation isnt high because a context switch uses no processing power, but when too many happen too quickly, your program grinds to a halt.

GIMP works normally as windows detects it needs more resources than chromium, and can allocate it suitable resources to run, giving it more processing time between switches to chromium processes.
